x86_64: fix post-EXIT #UD by correcting return-context stack layout

Step D residual bug: after ring3 SYS_EXIT, kernel-mode #UD at the
usermode_return_to_kernel ret instruction.

Root cause: in arch_x86_64_usermode_run() the inline-asm saved the
kernel return context with this push order:

    push label-1-RIP
    push rbp; push rbx; push r12..r15
    mov  %rsp, saved_rsp

So saved_rsp pointed at the *r15 slot*, not the RIP slot. When
arch_x86_64_usermode_return_to_kernel did `mov saved,%rsp; ret`,
the CPU popped r15's value as RIP and #UD'd.

Fix: reverse push order so the RIP slot ends up on top of the saved
frame and saved_rsp points directly at it:

    push rbp; push rbx; push r12..r15
    push label-1-RIP        <-- saved_rsp points here
    mov  %rsp, saved_rsp

The matching label-1 site now pops the six callee-saved registers
in reverse-push order and falls through to the function epilogue;
the standalone `addq $8,%rsp` slot-discard is no longer needed
because `ret` already consumed the RIP slot.

Verified under OVMF: hello64 ring3 runs WRITE/OPEN/READ/WRITE/CLOSE/
WRITE/EXIT cleanly, kernel returns to kmain, shell/init/vfs status
prints, kmain halts with no faults. QEMU log post-shutdown is empty.
